2500|$|However, {{while many}} groups work to provide Bibles for the military, {{sometimes}} promoting {{their relationships with}} retired or active duty chaplains, the actual use of military symbols—the emblem of the Department of Defense or emblems for one or more branches of the military—on Bibles available for purchase became a source of controversy in 2005. Some of these Bibles—printed and published by civilian publishing houses or churches—bear titles such as [...] "The Soldier’s Bible" [...] or [...] "The Airman’s Bible," [...] which (according to critics) when linked to the symbols might give the impression <b>that</b> <b>the</b> <b>military</b> <b>is</b> endorsing (or even [...] "establishing") religion in general, or the specific religion or faith group for whom one particular version of the Bible is considered holy.|$|E
